How do I tell the difference between fat & muscle when I am ready to inject?

Options
  • Mark as New
  • Bookmark
  • Subscribe to Direct Replies to This Post
  • Subscribe to RSS Feed
  • Highlight
  • Print
  • Email to a Friend
  • Report Inappropriate Content

‎11-11-2009 01:08 AM

After 37+ years of diabetes, you'd think I would have a question like this down, right? Well, what with health insurance changes, having to change hospital systems, etc. over the years, I have gradually eliminated some of the possible causes of my blood sugar's wild imitation of an excited dolphin -- up & down, up & down, 45 this morning, 345 at lunchtime today. And so it goes.

So one possible remaining issue is the way I inject my insulin. I know that I am supposed to inject into fat, not muscle. But how do I tell which I'm grabbing (fat or muscle) when I pinch?

This is something that I was never able to get an answer to when I attended all those diabetes classes. Now I'm unemployed, thinking that I might get COBRA, but, until I get it, or get a job w/ coverage, I can't just walk into the endocrinology clinic and ask something like this. I'd have to make an appointment, and pay for it somehow.

From what I've heard, skin is supposed to have an indigenous layer of fat underneath it. But we would never hear doctors warning us not to inject into muscle if there weren't a potential problem, right?

My ideal weight is 185-190, and I have gradually been gaining weight. I'm up to around 175+, now; added about 1 lb. a month over the years. So it's not as if I'm so thin that there is no fat to inject into.

How do I tell the difference between fat & muscle when I am ready to inject?
IHSscj
T1, diag in 1972, began home BG monitoring in about 1991. Began Animas pump.therapy 28 Jan 2013.

‎01-14-2010 04:26 PM

Find a spot you think you want to inject. Stand in front of the mirror with that part of your body having no clothing on.

If you look and smile, there is muscle.

If you roll your eyes, it is fat


You go to school to learn, not for a report card.
You use your meter to learn, not for a report card

Type 1 (LADA).. Novolog/Levemir

Adult onset T1

I hit muscle a number of times when I was using the longer needles, and occasionally with the shorts (I have very little fat on my arms, but preferred those sites for injections). You'll know when you hit muscle. Hurts -- like a deep hurt, not a pinch -- like a witch.

‎11-11-2009 02:46 AM

I am certainly no expert as I'm recently diagnosed. However, previously, I went through medical procedures that required both "fat" shots and "muscle" shots. From that experience, as long as you are using subcutaneous needles in the lower belly or upper thigh area, you won't hit the muscle. The needles for muscle shots are MUCH longer.

‎11-11-2009 03:57 AM

Well, I hit a muscle only once and that was with the old longer needle syringes. I was shooting in the arm and boy did it hurt! If you are using the short needles, it is very unlikely you will hit muscle. If you are paranoid about it, you can do the old 45 degree angle shot. Even if you do hit a muscle the only difference is more rapid insulin absorption. It is not going to cause a 345 BG.

Lots of things can cause swings. Hitting a muscle would be my least likely suspect.

Well I learned mine by Pictures showing me that

and A few inches above the Inner the Knee area..

been fine most of the time.. If I go too far one side or the other? Big Owies..


Many Females having More sensitve Skin, etc have harder problems and best to ask them for their tougher areas..


If your thinner, try the 1/2 Length Needles ..
and if you can't Pinch an Inch, try another area..
